After you have soldered in all the discrete components and got the circuit all hooked up, now 
you have to add the two RCA jacks for input from your Amiga, the two RCA jacks for output to 
your existing amp, and the socket for your CD ROM audio. For power, the neat and professional 
way to do it would be to make up a passthrough connector from the power plugs and sockets out 
of an old motherboard and powersupply, but chances are you've already bodged that up
anyway, seeing your A1200 doesn't need such connectors.
{p} {p}
{p} {p}
{bold}The passive audio mixer{nobold}
{p} {p}
If you are the lazy type, and find ICs scary, there is a simpler way to mix your audio. This is a 
cheap and nasty way of doing things, compared to our active mixer I've just described, but it 
works. It's really just a couple of variable resistors thrown together, but some people like to call it 
a 'Passive' audio mixer. It's passive because there isn't amplification, and the result is an output 
that is mixed ok, but weaker (hence the need for amplification..).
{p} {p}
If you take a close look at the schematic for the active mixer, you will see that before the two 
input signals for each channel go anywhere, they are joined together with a variable resistor. All 
the op-amp does is boosts the output signal. The actual 'mixing' is done by the resistor. This pre-
amplification is ideal for a professional situation, because if it wasn't boosted here, your main 
amp would be turned up a great deal more. If you've got cheap equipment, this might mean 
you have a constant background hiss, but it is something to avoid.
{p} {p}
So I'll give you the info you need to build a 'passive' mixer. It's really quite simple..
{p} {p}
What you need:
{p} {p}
- 2x 47k ohm variable trim pots/potentiometers{p}
- Some prototype matrix PCB (predrilled with copper pads) or veroboard, OR just solder the 
beggars on the spot with some hookup wire.{p}
- 4x RCA sockets (2x for Amiga -> mixer, 2x for mixer -> amp){p}
- Stereo RCA cable (mixer -> amp hookup){p}
- 1x Socket suitable for your CD ROM's audio output{p}
- 1x Zippy box or similar to house it all. Optionally, if your daring and don't mind smoke, you 
can just leave it dangle there.{p}
